    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense, but the \"instantaneous\" part is what's tripping me up. Einstein famously called it \"spooky action at a distance\" because it seemed to defy how things should work. Why did he find it so unsettling compared to just regular correlation?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Einstein's discomfort with entanglement stems from the fact that it appears to allow for faster-than-light communication, which contradicts the fundamental principles of special relativity. You see, in classical physics, information can't travel faster than the speed of light, and Einstein believed that this was a fundamental limit. \n\nBut with entanglement, it seems like the connection between particles can be instantaneous, which raises questions about the nature of space and time. It's like having a secret tunnel that allows information to travel between two points without crossing the space in between. Einstein's discomfort is rooted in the idea that this would allow for a kind of \"quantum teleportation\" or \"quantum messaging\" that would undermine the principles of relativity.\n\nTo put it in a more relatable way, imagine two messengers, one in New York and one in Los Angeles, who are supposed to meet at a designated point in the middle. In classical physics, the messenger in New York would have to send a message to the messenger in Los Angeles, which would then take time to arrive. But with entanglement, it's like the two messengers are connected by a magical string that allows them to communicate instantly, regardless of the distance between them",
      "source": "target",
